5yDnFQ.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*VFDgFw5hGP5yDnFQ.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*VFDgFw5hGP5yDnFQ.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*VFDgFw5hGP5yDnFQ.jpg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*VFDgFw5hGP5yDnFQ.jpg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">A simple problem…</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Take a number, any number. If it’s even, divide it by 2; if it’s odd, multiply it by 3 and add 1. <br></br>Take 10 for example. 10 is even, so you divide it by 2, which gives you 5. 5 is odd, so you multiply it by 3 and add 1, which gives you 16. 16 is even, so you divide it by 2, which gives you 8, then 4, then 2, then 1. Now 1 is odd, so you multiply it by 3 and add 1: you get 4. Only you know now what will happen from 4.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>You are stuck in a loop.</strong></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This is the statement of the Syracuse conjecture, the name of this problem: whatever the initial term N of the sequence, this one ends up inexorably looping on 4, 2, 1. <br></br><mark>In mathematics, a rule that has never been proven is called a conjecture. This rule may have been verified on millions of examples without being proven.</mark></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">… that nobody has managed to solve.</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Until now, mathematicians have used the brute force approach, which means trying all possibilities hoping to find an exception that would disprove the conjecture. Today they tested ²⁶⁸ possibilities, or about 300 quintillion (295,147,905,179,352,825,856 to be precise) numbers, and found that they all obey the conjecture. However, until one can write a proof for a positive integer “n” to cover all the numbers up to infinity, one cannot translate this conjecture into a theorem. Various attempts have been made to prove this conjecture but everyone seems to have satisfied the conditions of “almost” true, but not “absolutely” true. <br></br>In 2019, Terence Tao, the man with the highest IQ in the world, showed that almost all initial “n” values eventually iterate to a value less than f(n), for any function f() that grows to infinity, no matter how slow. “Almost all Syracuse orbits reach almost bounded values”. According to him, this is the closest thing to solving the Syracuse conjecture, without solving it!</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:38%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 300px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:600/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 600w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 300px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:600/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B 600w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:300/0*K6jGAiA33wEcBx5B"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Terence Tao, 230 IQ</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What about negative integers?<br></br>So far, we have been talking about “n positive integers”. Let’s take a look at negative numbers. In this case, we observe three distinct but disconnected loops:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">-2 =&gt; -1<br></br>-5 =&gt; -14=&gt; -7=&gt; -20 =&gt; -10<br></br>-17 =&gt; -50=&gt; -25=&gt; … =&gt; -34</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The pattern of the positive world is not reflected in the negative world. Intriguing…</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Math beauty</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The beauty of mathematics lies in the fact that statistical methods have so far worked up to 2⁶⁸ integers and still have not been able to prove the conjecture, however, it will only take one positive integer “n” to disprove it. 2²⁶⁸ is actually infinitesimal in the set of natural integers.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The beauty of mathematics also appears in the way we can represent it.<br></br>Here is the representation of the Collatz sequence of multiple positive integers, which is turned to one side when the number is even and to the other side when the number is odd. Elegant, isn’t it?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
