P0oniM3p2AL8EiL 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:890/0*GP0oniM3p2AL8EiL 890w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:445/0*GP0oniM3p2AL8EiL"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Numbers have always fascinated us because of their profoundly fundamental character. They are the basis of the most powerful tool that humans have developed to understand and illuminate the world around them: mathematics. We invent models, theorems and other theories to reinforce the brightness of this torch that guides us through the cave of our insignificance. And as soon as we move away from these representations, the unknown opens up to us. In this darkness is probably hidden an infinity of mysteries to which our intelligence will perhaps never be able to reach.<br></br><strong>The only thing is to know if the conjecture of Syracuse is part of it.</strong></p></div></div></div></section><?php include_once 'Elemental/footer.php'; ?>